1. INTRODUCTION

Genome-wide association study (GWAS) is a study design used to identify association between genetic variants and diseases or quantitative traits.1 Typically, GWAS is a hypothesis-free approach that involves looking for a single base-pair change in the DNA sequence (single nucleotide polymorphisms or SNPs) that occur with high frequency in the human genome.2 SNPs are said to be “associated” with disease/trait if certain SNPs are more commonly found in people with a disease/trait compared to those without the disease/trait. SNPs are typically used as markers of a genomic region, with most of them having a minimal impact on biological systems.3

In this exercise, you will learn how to perform the genome-wide association analysis using rvtests. Rvtests is a comprehensive tool developed to support genetic association analysis. Details about rvtests can be found on http://zhanxw.github.io/rvtests/. The phenotype of interest in todays’ practical is a metabolically related quaternary ammonium compound measured in blood, betaine. Genetic data includes genotypes imputed with Haplotype Reference Consortium imputation panel.

3.1 PHENOTYPE DATA

By default, *.pheno file is a file with one line per sample and at least 6 columns as illustrated below:

  • Column1: Study ID (‘fid’)
  • Column2: Individual ID (‘iid’; cannot be ‘0’)
  • Column3: ID of father (‘fatid’; ‘0’ if father isn’t in dataset)
  • Column4: ID of mother (‘matid’; ‘0’ if mother isn’t in dataset)
  • Column5: Sex (‘1’ = male, ‘2’ = female, ‘0’ = unknown)
  • Column6: Phenotype1 (quantitative values or ‘1’ = control, ‘2’ = case, ‘0’ = missing)

The *.covar file has a similar format as the phenotype file. The first five columns are the same as in the *.pheno file. Additionally, other columns with relevant covariates are also included.

Open the phenotype and covariate files in the R-Studio cloud. Explore the files by using dim and looking at the first few entries, e.g:

3.2. GENOTYPE DATA

By default, the *.vcf (Variant Call Format) file is a file format for storing genetic variation data. Even though VCF files are text files, they tend to be rather big. Therefore, for purposes of this exercise, you will explore a small example VCF file - Mydata.vcf.

In the web browser open the page https://samtools.github.io/hts-specs/VCFv4.2.pdf. This webpage is describing the VCF format and contains very useful information. The facts about the VCF files are as follows:

  • The VCF file starts with multiple meta-information lines (staring with ##). These lines describe what information can be found in the VCF. Not all VCF files contain the same information, therefore, the headers of two VCFs can be completely different.

  • Subsequently, the VCF file contains single header line (starting with #). The header line names the 8 fixed, mandatory columns. These columns are as follows:

    • CHROM - chromosome
    • POS - position (genomic coordinate on which the variant occurs)
    • ID - an optional unique identifier (typically the dbSNP variants identifier - rs number)
    • REF - reference base; the base listed in the reference genome
    • ALT - alternate base; the base observed in a sample/samples
    • QUAL - quality score
    • FILTER - filter status; PASS if position has passed all filters
    • INFO - additional information. Check the web page for data type.

  • After these mandatory columns, the VCF file could contain genotype information. The same type of data must be present for all samples. This is specified in FORMAT field. If present, the first sub-field of FORMAT field must always be genotype (GT). Check the web page for other data type. Subsequently, you will find the ID names of the samples in the VCF file.

  • Following the header are the data line containing information about a position in the genome.

Open Mydata.vcf file in R and answer the questions.

# Read header of the file

4. QUALITY CONTROL PRIOR GWAS

A crucial step of any GWAS is the use of appropriate quality control (QC). The QC is typically applied at the sample and SNP-specific level. In this paragraph we will focus on sample-level QC, while SNP-level QC will be discussed later. Sample-level QC includes filtering out samples with low call rates, evidence for different ethnic origin,relatedness/duplication, sex discrepancies and genotyping batch effects. Without extensive QC, GWAS will not generate reliable results. Here, we will provide details on the effects of different ethnic origin, relatedness and sex discrepancies in GWAS.

  1. Evidence of different ethnic origin - Population stratification occurs when the study samples comprise multiple groups of individuals who differ systematically in both genetic ancestry and the phenotype under investigation. Differences in ancestry would lead to spurious associations rather than true association of alleles to disease.There are several methods for observing and clustering ancestral groups. These methods use genome-wide level data to summarize genetic variance in variables that can be plotted to visualize genetic relationships between samples. When visualized alongside known reference populations, ancestral background can be identified among the sample. Below you will find a multidimensional scaling (MDS) plot. The study population is shown in red while color of other ancestral groups is displayed in the legend.

MDS plot

  1. Sample relatedness - The statistical association between genotypes and phenotypes could be biases by sample relatedness. Therefore, differences in the levels of relatedness need to be accounted for in GWAS.

  2. Sex discrepancies refer to difference between the sex recorded in the dataset and sex based on genotypes of sex chromosomes (X and Y). Sex discrepancies can indicate sample mix-ups. Sex discrepancy checks can also reveal sex chromosomal anomalies such as Turner syndrome (females having karyotype XO), Kleinfelter syndrome (males having karyotype XXY) etc.

5. ASSOCIATION ANALYSIS

Standard approach to identify genetic variants associated with phenotype in GWAS is linear or logistic regression. Statistical model for each SNP would be linear or logistic regression of phenotype on genotype while correcting for covariates.

The model for GWAS of betaine is as follows:

Betaine ~ constant + β1 x SNP + β2 x age + β3 x sex

In this file, you will obtain following columns:

  • N_INFORMATIVE - Number of samples that are analyzed for association
  • AF - Allele frequency
  • INFORMATIVE_ALT_AC - The number of alternative alleles in the analyzed samples
  • CALL_RATE - The fraction of non-missing alleles
  • HWE_PVALUE - Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium
  • N_REF/N_HET/N_ALT - Number of samples carrying homozygous reference /heterozygous/ homozygous alternative alleles
  • U_STAT, SQRT_V_STAT - U and V statistics are score statistics and their covariance matrix
  • ALT_EFFSIZE - Estimated effect size (continuous outcomes) or log odds-ratio (binary outcome)

7. VISUALIZATION

Visualization of GWAS results is necessary to get the overview of large amount of information and to be able to interpret the results. Typically, QQ plot, Manhattan plot, and LocusZoom plot are made after the GWAS.

7.1 QQ PLOT

The QQ plot is a plot representing the deviation of the observed p-values plotted against expected p-values from a theoretical χ2-distribution. If the observed values correspond to the expected values, all points are on or near the middle line between the x- and y-axis. In a case some observed p-values are more significant than expected, points will move towards the y-axis. QQ plot based on Myresults.txt.gz can be generated using the code below.

qq = function(pvector, ...) { if (!is.numeric(pvector)) stop("D'oh! P value vector is not numeric.") 
pvector <- pvector[!is.na(pvector) & pvector<1 & pvector>0] 
o = -log10(sort(pvector,decreasing=F)) 
e = -log10(ppoints(length(pvector) )) 
plot(e,o,pch=19,cex=1,xlab=expression(Expected~~-log[10](italic(p))),ylab=expression(Observed~~-log[10](italic(p))), xlim=c(0,max(e)),
ylim=c(0,max(o)), ...) 
abline(0,1,col="red") }

qq(results$PVALUE)

Additionally, the deviation of the distribution of the observed test statistic compared to the distribution of the expected test statistic can also be quantified. Common way to do this is to calculate genomic inflation factor, also known as lambda gc (λgc). By definition, λgc is defined as the median of the resulting chi-squared test statistics divided by the expected median of the chi-squared distribution.

8. POST GWAS QUALITY CONTROL

The post GWAS QC is typically applied at the SNP-specific level and it consists of filtering out non reliable SNPs based on allele frequency, Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium (HWE), call rate and imputation quality.

  1. Most GWAS studies begin by filtering the variants by the allele frequency (AF). Variant with a low minor AF (MAF) are rare and therefore power for detecting association with phenotype of interest is lacking. Also, these variants are prone to genotyping errors. Typically, the MAF threshold depends on the size of study population. Commonly used thresholds are 0.01 and 0.05.

  2. HWE is a fundamental principal of population genetics, which states that “genotype frequencies in a population remain constant between generations in the absence of disturbance by outside factors”. Typically, SNPs deviating from Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium are excluded.

  3. Call rate for a given SNP is defined as the proportion of individuals in the study for which the corresponding SNP information is not missing. A high rate of missing data at a SNP locus is considered an indication of inaccurate genotype calls. A standard rule is filtering for SNPs with call rates ≥95 or 99%.

  4. Imputation quality - Commercial SNP genotyping arrays do not have complete coverage of the human genome. Therefore, to improve both coverage and power of a GWAS we use genotype imputation. Based on the linkage disequilibrium (LD) patterns derived from directly genotyped markers and comparing them to a suitable reference population, the alleles of ungenotyped SNPs can be inferred. Imputation quality can be assessed by the internal quality metrics obtained from each imputation protocol. These values range from 0 to 1, where a higher value indicates increased quality of an imputed SNP.
